movieBio.text:
The son of a bricklayer, British rock artist [rovilink="P 85122"]Eric Clapton[/rovilink] attended Kingston Art School before choosing the quicksilver life of a street musician. [rovilink="P"]Clapton[/rovilink]'s guitar prowess did not go unrecognized for long, and soon he was aligned with the Yardbirds, a major Mersey-beat band of the 1960s. [rovilink="P"]Clapton[/rovilink] owns the distinction of appearing with three of the most popular rock aggregations in music history: [rovilink="P 85122"]The Yardbirds[/rovilink],  Cream and Blind Faith.  So devoted were [rovilink="P"]Clapton[/rovilink]'s  followers that, by 1970, graffiti began popping up all over the world proclaiming "Clapton Is God." Even into the 1990s, [rovilink="P"]Clapton[/rovilink] has earned several Grammy awards for his ongoing musical contributions. Most of [rovilink="P"]Clapton[/rovilink]'s  film appearances have been in concert or "retrospective" movies like [rovilink="V    10717"]Concert for Bangladesh[/rovilink] (71), [rovilink="V"]The Last Waltz[/rovilink] (78) and [rovilink="V     9614"]Chuck Berry Hail! Hail! Rock N Roll[/rovilink] (87). 

His signature solo hit "Layla" was used memorably by Martin Scorsese in this 1990 gangster masterpiece Goodfellas, and he scored a huge hit with "Tears In Heaven" which featured prominently in the 1991 film Rush. In addition to a number of concert films and music documentaries, Clapton provided some of the most intimate remembrances of George Harrison in the [rovilink="P"]Scorsese[/rovilink] directed biography George Harrison: Living in the Material World.
movieBio.author: Hal Erickson

musicBio.text:
By the time [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Eric Clapton[/roviLink] launched his solo career with the release of his self-titled debut album in mid-1970, he was long established as one of the world's major rock stars due to his group affiliations -- [roviLink="MN0000489303"]the Yardbirds[/roviLink], [roviLink="MN0000238506"]John Mayall's Bluesbreakers[/roviLink], [roviLink="MN0000112462"]Cream[/roviLink], and [roviLink="MN0000760154"]Blind Faith[/roviLink] -- which had demonstrated his claim to being the best rock guitarist of his generation. That it took [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] so long to go out on his own, however, was evidence of a degree of reticence unusual for one of his stature. And his debut album, though it spawned the Top 40 hit "After Midnight," was typical of his self-effacing approach: it was, in effect, an album by the group he had lately been featured in, [roviLink="MN0000239235"]Delaney & Bonnie & Friends[/roviLink].
Not surprisingly, before his solo debut had even been released, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] had retreated from his solo stance, assembling from the [roviLink="MN0000239235"]D&B&F[/roviLink] ranks the personnel for a group, [roviLink="MN0000817369"]Derek & the Dominos[/roviLink], with whom he played for most of 1970 and recorded the landmark album [roviLink="MW0000650067"]Layla and Other Assorted Love Songs[/roviLink]. [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] was largely inactive in 1971 and 1972, due to heroin addiction, but he performed a comeback concert at the Rainbow Theatre in London on January 13, 1973, resulting in the album [roviLink="MW0000193259"]Eric Clapton's Rainbow Concert[/roviLink] (September 1973). But [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] did not launch a sustained solo career until July 1974, when he released [roviLink="MW0000649978"]461 Ocean Boulevard[/roviLink], which topped the charts and spawned the number one single "I Shot the Sheriff." 
The persona [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] established over the next decade was less that of guitar hero than arena rock star with a weakness for ballads. The follow-ups to [roviLink="MW0000649978"]461 Ocean Boulevard[/roviLink], [roviLink="MW0000649981"]There's One in Every Crowd[/roviLink] (March 1975), the live [roviLink="MW0000189487"]E.C. Was Here[/roviLink] (August 1975), and [roviLink="MW0000189488"]No Reason to Cry[/roviLink] (August 1976), were less successful. But [roviLink="MW0000189410"]Slowhand[/roviLink] (November 1977), which featured both the powerful "Cocaine" (written by [roviLink="MN0000119651"]J.J. Cale[/roviLink], who had also written "After Midnight") and the hit singles "Lay Down Sally" and "Wonderful Tonight," was a million-seller. Its follow-ups, [roviLink="MW0000189372"]Backless[/roviLink] (November 1978), featuring the Top Ten hit "Promises," the live [roviLink="MW0000118513"]Just One Night[/roviLink] (April 1980), and [roviLink="MW0000189486"]Another Ticket[/roviLink] (February 1981), featuring the Top Ten hit "I Can't Stand It," were all big sellers.
[roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink]'s popularity waned somewhat in the first half of the '80s, as the albums [roviLink="MW0000649980"]Money and Cigarettes[/roviLink] (February 1983), [roviLink="MW0000649979"]Behind the Sun[/roviLink] (March 1985), and [roviLink="MW0000193257"]August[/roviLink] (November 1986) indicated a certain career stasis. But he was buoyed up by the release of the box set retrospective [roviLink="MW0000193683"]Crossroads[/roviLink] (April 1988), which seemed to remind his fans of how great he was. [roviLink="MW0000654245"]Journeyman[/roviLink] (November 1989) was a return to form. It would be his last new studio album for nearly five years, though in the interim he would suffer greatly and enjoy surprising triumph. On March 20, 1991, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink]'s four-year-old son was killed in a fall. While he mourned, he released a live album, [roviLink="MW0000268925"]24 Nights[/roviLink] (October 1991), culled from his annual concert series at Royal Albert Hall in London, and prepared a movie soundtrack, [roviLink="MW0000271075"]Rush[/roviLink] (January 1992). The soundtrack featured a song written for his son, "Tears in Heaven," that became a massive hit single.
In March 1992, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] recorded a concert for [muzeItalic]MTV Unplugged[/muzeItalic] which, when released on an album in August, became his biggest-selling record ever. Two years later, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] returned with a blues album, [roviLink="MW0000119071"]From the Cradle[/roviLink], which became one of his most successful albums, both commercially and critically. [roviLink="MW0000180899"]Crossroads, Vol. 2: Live in the Seventies[/roviLink], a box set chronicling his live work from the '70s, was released to mixed reviews. In early 1997, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink], billing himself by the pseudonym "[roviLink="MN0002311342"]X-Sample[/roviLink]," collaborated with keyboardist/producer [roviLink="MN0000040214"]Simon Climie[/roviLink] as the ambient new age and trip-hop duo [roviLink="MN0000741924"]T.D.F.[/roviLink] The duo released [roviLink="MW0000092409"]Retail Therapy[/roviLink] to mixed reviews in early 1997. 
[roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] retained [roviLink="MN0000040214"]Climie[/roviLink] as his collaborator for [roviLink="MW0000033769"]Pilgrim[/roviLink], his first album of new material since 1989's [roviLink="MW0000654245"]Journeyman[/roviLink]. [roviLink="MW0000033769"]Pilgrim[/roviLink] was greeted with decidedly mixed reviews upon its spring 1998 release, but the album debuted at number four and stayed in the Top Ten for several weeks on the success of the single "My Father's Eyes." In 2000, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] teamed up with old friend [roviLink="MN0000059156"]B.B. King[/roviLink] on [roviLink="MW0000066846"]Riding with the King[/roviLink], a set of blues standards and material from contemporary singer/songwriters. Another solo outing, entitled [roviLink="MW0000119706"]Reptile[/roviLink], followed in early 2001. Three years later, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] issued [roviLink="MW0000329329"]Me and Mr. Johnson[/roviLink], a collection of tunes honoring the Mississippi-born bluesman [roviLink="MN0000832288"]Robert Johnson[/roviLink]. Released in 2005, [roviLink="MW0000210445"]Back Home[/roviLink], [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink]'s 14th album of original material, reflected his ease with fatherhood. Also in 2005, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] unexpectedly teamed with [roviLink="MN0000152312"]Jack Bruce[/roviLink] and [roviLink="MN0000655273"]Ginger Baker[/roviLink] for a [roviLink="MN0000112462"]Cream[/roviLink] reunion that included May concerts at London's Royal Albert Hall and shows at New York's Madison Square Garden in October, with the former being compiled for a live release that fall. 
This turned out to be the first of many reunions and looks back for [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink]. In 2006, he elevated the profile of his latter-day idol [roviLink="MN0000119651"]J.J. Cale[/roviLink] by recording an album-long duet, [roviLink="MW0000562803"]The Road to Escondido[/roviLink]. The following year he released his autobiography -- accompanied by a new career compilation called [roviLink="MW0000749969"]The Complete Clapton[/roviLink] -- which focused more on his trials with addiction and subsequent recovery than his musical career. In 2008, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] began playing regular shows with his old [roviLink="MN0000760154"]Blind Faith[/roviLink] partner [roviLink="MN0000045313"]Steve Winwood[/roviLink], gigs that were captured on the 2009 double-live set [roviLink="MW0000818043"]Live from Madison Square Garden[/roviLink]. [roviLink="MN0000045313"]Winwood[/roviLink] also appeared on [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink]'s next studio album, 2010's [roviLink="MW0000624369"]Clapton[/roviLink], which was a collaboration-heavy affair also featuring [roviLink="MN0000119651"]Cale[/roviLink], [roviLink="MN0000080780"]Sheryl Crow[/roviLink], [roviLink="MN0000933172"]Allen Toussaint[/roviLink], and [roviLink="MN0000961688"]Wynton Marsalis[/roviLink]. In 2011, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] returned the favor to [roviLink="MN0000961688"]Marsalis[/roviLink] by collaborating on the live concert album [roviLink="MW0002193948"]Play the Blues: Live from Jazz at Lincoln Center[/roviLink]. 
[roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] parted ways with [roviLink="MN"]Warner[/roviLink] after [roviLink="MW0000624369"]Clapton[/roviLink], and he chose to set up his own [roviLink="MN"]Bushbranch[/roviLink] imprint on [roviLink="MN0000741158"]Gary Hoey[/roviLink]'s independent label [roviLink="MN"]Surfdog[/roviLink]. His first album for the label was [roviLink="MW0002483535"]Old Sock[/roviLink], largely a collection of old songs the guitarist loved. It reached the Top Ten in the U.S. and Great Britain. In the fall of 2013, [roviLink="MN"]Warner Bros.[/roviLink] released [roviLink="MW0002618121"]Crossroads Guitar Festival 2013[/roviLink], and his [roviLink="MW0000081583"]Unplugged[/roviLink] album was expanded and remastered by [roviLink="MN"]Rhino[/roviLink]. Early the following year, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] announced that a new album, [roviLink="MW0002679009"]The Breeze: An Appreciation of J.J. Cale[/roviLink], would be issued in July, one year on from the passing of his key inspiration. The tribute album included contributions from artists such as [roviLink="MN0000583959"]Willie Nelson[/roviLink], [roviLink="MN0000239827"]John Mayer[/roviLink], [roviLink="MN0000612716"]Tom Petty[/roviLink], and [roviLink="MN0000831236"]Mark Knopfler[/roviLink]. A collection of his [roviLink="MN"]Warner[/roviLink] recordings called [roviLink="MW0002836250"]Forever Man[/roviLink] saw a spring 2015 release. [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] returned in May of 2016 with [roviLink="MW0002922480"]I Still Do[/roviLink], his third album for [roviLink="MN"]Surfdog[/roviLink]. It found him reuniting with [roviLink="MW0000189410"]Slowhand[/roviLink] producer [roviLink="MN0000950233"]Glyn Johns[/roviLink]; the album debuted at six on the Billboard Top 200. Later that year, [roviLink="MN0000187478"]Clapton[/roviLink] released [roviLink="MW0002970500"]Live in San Diego[/roviLink], a double-disc album featuring a 2007 concert with [roviLink="MN0000119651"]J.J. Cale[/roviLink]. ~ Stephen Thomas Erlewine

musicBioOverview.author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
musicBioOverview.overview: Prior to Eric Clapton, the idea of the guitar hero didn't exist in rock & roll. There were flashy players but nothing along the lines of Clapton, who rocketed to fame in the '60s as the guitarist for the Yardbirds and Cream. Clapton eased into a solo career in 1970 but he was so reticent to step to the front of the stage he adopted a pseudonym for [roviLink="MW0000650067"]Layla and Other Assorted Love Songs[/roviLink] by Derek & the Dominos. By the end of the '70s he embraced his role as the preeminent guitarist of his generation, tempering his virtuosity with pretty ballads. That sensitive side shone on his biggest hit, 1992's [roviLink="MW0000081583"]MTV Unplugged[/roviLink], which also reconnected him with the blues roots upon which his entire career lay. ~ Stephen Thomas Erlewine

musicBioOverview.author: William Ruhlmann
musicBioOverview.overview: À l'époque où Eric Clapton émerge en tant qu'artiste populaire en solo, il s'est déjà imposé comme l'un des plus grands guitaristes rock du monde après avoir joué avec les Yardbirds, les Bluesbreakers de John Mayall, Cream, Blind Faith, et Derek & the Dominos. Les débuts de sa carrière en solo propulsent le tube "After Midnight" dans le Top 40 en 1970, mais il faut attendre la sortie en 1974 de 461 Ocean Boulevard pour que Clapton atteigne la première place avec "I Shot the Sheriff." Le plus gros succès de Clapton a lieu en 1992, quand il enregistre un concert pour MTV Unplugged, où il joue des versions très populaires de "Tears in Heaven" et "Layla.". ~ William Ruhlmann

musicBioOverview.author: William Ruhlmann
musicBioOverview.overview: К тому времени, когда Eric Clapton стал популярным сольным исполнителем, он уже зарекомендовал себя как серьезный {\рок}-гитарист во всем мире благодаря работе с такими группами, как the Yardbirds, John Mayall's Bluesbreakers, Cream, Blind Faith и Derek & the Dominos. Его сольный дебют дал начало хиту "After Midnight", попавшему в список лучших 40 песен 1970 года; однако только после выпуска альбома 461 Ocean Boulevard в 1974 году синглу Клэптона "I Shot the Sheriff" посчастливилось занять первое место. Самый большой успех пришел к Clapton в 1992 году, когда он записал концерт для MTV Unplugged, в котором были представлены безумно популярные версии "Tears in Heaven" и "Layla". ~ William Ruhlmann

musicBioOverview.author: William Ruhlmann
musicBioOverview.overview: Tegen de tijd dat Eric Clapton als soloartiest bekend werd stond hij al bekend als een van 's werelds belangrijkste rockgitaristen door zijn werk met the Yardbirds, John Mayall's Bluesbreakers, Cream, Blind Faith en Derek & the Dominos. Zijn solodebuut zorgde in 1970 voor de Top 40 hit "After Midnight", maar pas na de uitgave van 461 Ocean Boulevard in 1974 had Clapton een nummer 1 single met "I Shot the Sheriff". Clapton's grootste succes kwam in 1992, toen hij een concert opnam voor MTV Unplugged dat de enorm populaire versies bevatte van "Tears in Heaven" en "Layla". ~ William Ruhlmann

musicBioOverview.author: William Ruhlmann
musicBioOverview.overview: Ai tempi, Eric Clapton emerse come artista popolare solista, godendo già della reputazione di uno dei maggiori chitarristi rock del mondo grazie al suo lavoro con the Yardbirds, John Mayall's Bluesbreakers, Cream, Blind Faith, e Derek & the Dominos. Il suo debutto da solista con il brano "After Midnight" balza ai vertici della classifica Top 40 nel 1970, ma solo nel 1974 con l'uscita di 461 Ocean Boulevard Clapton sale alla ribalta della cronaca con l’eccezionale singolo "I Shot the Sheriff.". I principali successi di Clapton arrivarono nel 1992, quando registrò un concerto per MTV Unplugged interpretando i popolari brani "Tears in Heaven" e "Layla.". ~ William Ruhlmann

musicBioOverview.author: William Ruhlmann
musicBioOverview.overview: Als Eric Clapton schließlich als beliebter Solo-Künstler in Erscheinung trat, hatte er sich schon lange als einer der weltbesten Rock-Gitarristen aufgrund seiner Arbeit mit the Yardbirds, John Mayall's Bluesbreakers, Cream, Blind Faith und Derek & the Dominos etabliert. Sein Solodebüt begann 1970 mit dem Top 40 - Hit "After Midnight",aber es sollte bis zur Veröffentlichung des 1974er Albums 461 Ocean Boulevard dauern, dass Clapton mit "I Shot the Sheriff" eine Nummer 1 Single herausbrachte. Claptons größter Erfolg stellte sich 1992 ein, als er für MTV Unplugged ein Konzert aufnahm, dass außerordentlich beliebte Versionen von "Tears in Heaven" und "Layla" enthielt. ~ William Ruhlmann

Aún antes de transformarse en una estrella solista, Eric Clapton ya había acumulado los méritos necesarios para ser considerado uno de los mejores y más importantes guitarristas de la historia del rock, grabando varios discos fundamentales con The Yardbirds, John Mayall's Bluesbreakers, Cream, Blind Faith y Derek & The Dominos. Su carrera en solitario, iniciada en 1970 con Eric Clapton, fue seguramente menos innovadora - en los ochenta fue prácticamente un artista de pop masivo mientras que de los noventa en adelante se mostró cada vez más apegado al blues tradicional - pero quizás aún más exitosa. Los puntos salientes de su extensa discografía solista son 461 Ocean Boulevard (1974), Slowhand (1977), MTV Unplugged (1992) y la recopilación Crossroads (1988), así como las colaboraciones con sus admirados B.B. King y J.J. Cale.

factsheets.details:
• Raised by his grandparents.
  • Believed that his mother Patricia, who had him out of wedlock at 16, was his sister; learned the truth when he was 9.
  • Never met his biological father, who was a Canadian soldier stationed in Britain during World War II.
  • Introduced to the blues by Uncle Mac's Children's Hour, a children's radio show that occasionally played blues songs. 
  • Received his first guitar at age 13.
  • Joined his first band, the Roosters, at age 17, in early 1963.
  • Recruited to the Yardbirds in October 1963; earned the nickname "Slowhand" during his stint with the band.
  • Quit the Yardbirds because of their move to a pop sound with the hit single "For Your Love."
  • Joined John Mayall's Bluesbreakers, a blues-purist group, in 1965. It was with them that he earned another nickname: "God."
  • Formed Cream with Jack Bruce and Ginger Baker in July 1966.
  • Broke up Cream in 1968 due to personality conflicts and a desire to get away from music driven by extended guitar solos. 
  • Played lead guitar on the Beatles' "While My Guitar Gently Weeps."
  • Became a close friend of George Harrison. 
  • Formed the supergroup Blind Faith with Steve Winwood, Ginger Baker and Ric Grech after Cream disbanded. The band released one album before breaking up.
  • Though unsure of himself as a singer, he pressed on with vocals and released his self-titled solo debut in 1970.
  • Formed Derek and the Dominos in 1970, releasing the classic Layla and Other Assorted Love Songs album that same year.
  • Inspired by his then-unrequited love for Pattie Boyd, wife of George Harrison, to write "Layla."
  • Wrote the Grammy-winning "Tears From Heaven" for his 4-year-old son Conor, who died in 1991 when he fell from a 53rd-floor apartment in New York City.
  • Struggled with addictions to alcohol and heroin, finally becoming sober in 1987.
  • Founded Crossroads Centre, an alcohol-drug treatment facility in Antigua, in 1998.
  • Has played guitar on songs by (among many others) Bob Dylan, Aretha Franklin, George Harrison, Elton John, B.B. King, John Lennon and Frank Zappa.
  • Three-time inductee into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame: with the Yardbirds (1992), Cream (1993) and on his own (2000).
  • Published the acclaimed, best-selling Clapton: The Autobiography in 2007.
